### **Fix 3 — `docs/design/branding.md`**

Add a new section (§5) that makes the Identity Tier Priority a first-class branding principle, so any agent reading the branding doc before touching the nav will see it:

Add after the existing content (end of file or after §4):

```markdown
---

## 5. Identity Tier Priority

**Rule:** Site chrome elements are ranked by compression tolerance. Higher tiers never yield to lower tiers.

| Tier | Element | Compression tolerance | CSS mechanism |
|------|---------|----------------------|---------------|
| **1 — Rigid** | Logo mark + "Yilan Gao" name | **Zero.** Never wraps, never shrinks, at any viewport width. | `flex-shrink: 0` + `white-space: nowrap` + `min-width: max-content` on the logo; `flex-wrap: nowrap` on the nav row |
| **2 — Yield** | Tagline / role blurb ("Designer, AI systems experience…") | Wraps to a maximum of 2 lines. Designated absorber for viewport squeeze. | `min-width: 0` + `-webkit-line-clamp: 2` |
| **3 — Optional** | Nav links | Present only when populated. Short labels; should not wrap but are lower priority than Tiers 1–2. | `white-space: nowrap` |

**Why Tier 1 is absolute:** The name "Yilan Gao" is not a UI element — it is the site's foundational identity claim. A wrapping name signals a broken layout before the user reads a single word of content. The asymmetry is intentional: the tagline exists *to be squeezable* so the name never has to be.

**Where this applies:** Any nav bar, header, or identity strip on yilangao.com. This is not limited to the current `Navigation` component — it applies to any future composition where a name or logo mark appears alongside secondary text.

**See:** AP-066 (design anti-pattern), FB-146 (original nav logo wrapping report).
```

---

## Summary

**Diagnosis:** The nav logo `Yilan Gao` wraps to two lines under squeeze despite `flex-shrink: 0` on `.logo` and `white-space: nowrap` on `.logoText`. The failure has two vectors: (1) `.navInner` lacked `flex-wrap: nowrap`, so the row itself was allowed to break; (2) the `.logo` container (`inline-flex` link) lacked `white-space: nowrap` and `min-width: max-content` at its own level, leaving a gap where the browser could internally rearrange the mark + text under extreme compression.

**Root cause:** **AP-066** (Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text) — the triple-lock (`flex-shrink: 0` + `white-space: nowrap` + `min-width: max-content` on the element, plus `flex-wrap: nowrap` on the outer row) was incomplete. Only one of the four declarations was present. The Identity Tier Priority principle was also not yet formally codified — it existed only in code comments, not as a named, discoverable rule.

**Fix — three files:**
1. **`src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`** — add `flex-wrap: nowrap` to `.navInner`; add `white-space: nowrap` + `min-width: max-content` to `.logo`; add `white-space: nowrap` to `.link`; change `.links` to `align-items: flex-start` so a 2-line tagline aligns to the optical top rather than centering vertically against the logo
2. **`docs/design-anti-patterns.md`** — update AP-066 to formally name and define the Identity Tier Priority rule with the canonical three-tier table and the four required CSS declarations
3. **`docs/design/branding.md`** — add §5 Identity Tier Priority as a first-class branding rule with the tier table, so any agent reading branding before touching the nav will find it without needing to search the anti-patterns catalog

**Principle:** The logo is Tier 1 — rigid, non-negotiable, protected by the full triple-lock. The tagline is Tier 2 — the designated yield point. The tagline exists *so the logo never has to compromise*. This is an identity rule, not a layout preference. (AP-066)
